{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539085"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:36:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:36:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16430"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16430","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16430"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.04,0.22,0.56,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9121"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112503"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9121"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16430"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94537"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1098"},{"type":"tags","id":"1569"},{"type":"tags","id":"2913"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21673"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35631"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46191"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112503"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with fatigue and feeling generally unwell. Her medical history includes hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus, idiopathic intracranial hypertension, and ankylosing spondylitis. She has a penicillin allergy. One week ago she was commenced on moxifloxacin for a community-acquired pneumonia. She has not been able to take her regular medications due to financial pressures, but was able to re-commence all of her medications two weeks ago. These include ramipril, moxonidine, dapagliflozin, gliclazide, acetazolamide, and naproxen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVenous blood gas analysis reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 7.32 (7.32-7.42)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpCO2 38 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHCO3- 19 mmol/L (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENa+ 136 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EK+ 3.5 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECl- 111 mmol/L (95-105)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely responsible for these acid-base changes?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Moxifloxacin","Moxonidine","Dapagliflozin","Acetazolamide","Naproxen"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a normal anion gap metabolic acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcetazolamide\u003C/strong\u003E is a carbonic anhydrase inhibitor that causes bicarbonate wasting in the proximal tubule, leading to a normal anion gap metabolic acidosis. This medication is commonly used to treat idiopathic intracranial hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMoxifloxacin\u003C/strong\u003E is a fluoroquinolone antibiotic that does not typically cause acid-base disturbances. While it can rarely cause lactic acidosis, this would present as a high anion gap metabolic acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMoxonidine\u003C/strong\u003E is a centrally-acting antihypertensive that does not directly affect acid-base balance. It works through stimulation of central imidazoline receptors to reduce sympathetic outflow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDapagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E is a sodium-glucose cotransporter-2 (SGLT2) inhibitor that can cause ketoacidosis, particularly in type 1 diabetes. However, this would present as a high anion gap metabolic acidosis, not the normal anion gap acidosis seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaproxen\u003C/strong\u003E, like other NSAIDs, can cause a high anion gap metabolic acidosis through various mechanisms including lactic acidosis or ketoacidosis, particularly in overdose. It does not cause a normal anion gap metabolic acidosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to this question is recognising the pattern of normal anion gap metabolic acidosis and knowing that carbonic anhydrase inhibitors like acetazolamide characteristically cause this acid-base disturbance through their mechanism of action in the kidney.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Acetazolamide causes a normal anion gap metabolic acidosis by inhibiting carbonic anhydrase in the proximal tubule.","Normal anion gap metabolic acidosis can be distinguished from high anion gap metabolic acidosis through calculation of the anion gap."],"references":["Khashayar Farzam, Abdullah M. Acetazolamide. In: StatPearls [online]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/books/NBK532282/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94537"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16430"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94537"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-02T08:08:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-02T08:12:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9121"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112503"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms"